<article>
    <h1>MU&#xAD;SIC DOC&#xAD;U&#xAD;MEN&#xAD;TARY SHAWN MEN&#xAD;DES: IN WON&#xAD;DER (NC16)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201204/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-04"><time>2020-12-04</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>83 min­utes/Net­flix</p>
    <p>This Net­flix doc­u­men­tary film is a lead-up to Cana­dian singer Shawn Men­des’ (above) fourth al­bum</p>
    <p>Won­der, which drops to­day. It prom­ises to give a deeper in­sight into the per­sonal life of one of pop’s most re­cent wun­derkinds.</p>
    <p>And we do get plenty of be­hind-the-scene footage – from him show­er­ing in a Brazil­ian ho­tel room and back­stage go­ing-ons to qual­ity time with his fam­ily at their Toronto home and song­writ­ing ses­sions.</p>
    <p>When he loses his voice dur­ing a world tour and is forced to can­cel a ma­jor show, he weeps and calls his mother.</p>
    <p>Still, one feels that there is a lot more that can be re­vealed about who Men­des re­ally is be­hind the pop idol ve­neer.</p>
    <p>His girl­friend and fel­low pop star Camila Ca­bello fea­tures promi­nently. Ev­ery song he writes is about her, he gushes.</p>
    <p>Given the mas­sive tabloid in­ter­est in their re­la­tion­ship, cyn­ics might call her cameos a bla­tant way to sell the doc­u­men­tary. But it is gen­uinely touch­ing to see them re­live their early years as friends be­fore be­com­ing ro­man­ti­cally in­volved.</p>

